<%# Docs chapter 01 — the library. Where every piece of data comes from.
    Copy rule: simple words, no hyphens in visible text. %>
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <%- include('../partials/head', { title: 'The library — how it works' }) %>
</head>
<body class="min-h-screen bg-paper font-sans text-ink antialiased">
  <%- include('../partials/frame') %>
  <%- include('../partials/nav') %>

  <main class="relative mx-auto max-w-6xl overflow-hidden px-6 py-12">
    <span class="pointer-events-none absolute -right-10 top-6 select-none font-serif text-[15rem] font-extrabold leading-none text-ink/[0.04]" aria-hidden="true">蔵</span>

    <div class="reveal relative">
      <%- include('../partials/docs-header') %>

      <div class="mt-10 max-w-3xl space-y-5 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-ink/85">
        <p>
          Every recommendation starts long before you open a page. It starts
          with a library: more than <span class="tabular-nums">38,000</span>
          anime stored in our own database, on our own machine. Nothing is
          fetched while you browse. Every page you open is answered from
          data that is already here. This chapter explains where each piece
          of that library comes from.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="mt-12">
        <span class="font-serif text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight">一覧</span>
        <span class="jp-sub">ichiran — the catalog itself</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="mt-5 max-w-3xl space-y-5 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-ink/85">
        <p>
          The list of titles comes from a community project that merges the
          big anime tracking sites into one open file, refreshed every week.
          One download gives us every anime with its titles, year, season,
          format, episode count, community score, studio credits and cover
          art, plus the links that connect each entry to its page on every
          major tracking site.
        </p>
        <p>
          We keep Japanese works and we keep them honestly: a sweep checked
          every entry against its country of origin and removed more than
          two thousand strays that were never anime to begin with. Adult
          works are filtered out at the database layer, everywhere, with no
          toggle. Dark and violent shows are not adult works and they all
          stay, because they are part of the medium.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="mt-12">
        <span class="font-serif text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight">語り部</span>
        <span class="jp-sub">kataribe — the two storytellers</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="mt-5 max-w-3xl space-y-5 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-ink/85">
        <p>
          Each anime carries up to two summaries, fetched once and stored.
          The first is the fan summary from MyAnimeList: warm, written to
          make you curious, good at describing how a show <em>feels</em>.
          The second is the plot section from Wikipedia: cooler, written to
          inform, good at describing what actually <em>happens</em>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Keeping both was a deliberate choice. The two texts describe the
          same story from different heights, and the engine fingerprints
          both, so a show can match on its mood, on its plot machinery, or
          on both at once. Where Wikipedia has no plot section, the fan
          summary carries the load alone. Both raw texts stay on the anime
          page with their sources named, and the Wikipedia text is shared
          under its Creative Commons license, credited in the footer of
          every page.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="mt-12">
        <span class="font-serif text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight">札と類</span>
        <span class="jp-sub">fuda to rui — tags, genres and studios</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="mt-5 max-w-3xl space-y-5 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-ink/85">
        <p>
          Tags arrive merged from several communities, which means several
          spelling habits. Left alone, the four spellings of science
          fiction would count as four unrelated labels, and two shows
          sharing "the same tag" under different spellings would look like
          strangers. A curated list of 49 spelling rules folds those
          variants into one canonical tag each, and growing that list is
          normal maintenance, not a special event.
        </p>
        <p>
          Genres turned out to be hiding inside the tags: the merged data
          had folded each site's genre list into the tag pile. We recovered
          the eighteen canonical genres from there, which covers more than
          eighty percent of the catalog, including thousands of titles that
          the usual genre sources cannot serve at all.
        </p>
        <p>
          Studio credits ride along with the catalog file, and so does the
          relations graph: roughly <span class="tabular-nums">32,000</span>
          links that say "these two entries belong to the same family",
          which chapter four turns into the franchise checkpoint.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="mt-12">
        <span class="font-serif text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight">遅い車線</span>
        <span class="jp-sub">osoi shasen — the slow lane</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="mt-5 max-w-3xl space-y-5 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-ink/85">
        <p>
          Some data cannot arrive in one download. The source material of
          each show, whether it was born as manga, a novel, a game or an
          original work, is being filled in by a slow crawl that asks for
          one title per second, politely, around the clock. Signals that
          depend on data like this are written to stay quiet where the data
          is missing rather than guess, and they grow stronger on their own
          as the rows fill in. The status labels in chapter three tell you
          honestly which signals are at full strength today.
        </p>
      </div>

      <%- include('../partials/docs-pager') %>
    </div>
  </main>

  <%- include('../partials/footer') %>
</body>
</html>
